<h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Glossary</h1>

<blockquote class="border-l-4 border-gray-300 pl-4 py-2 my-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Each term includes <strong class="font-semibold">definition â†’ guitar-specific note â†’ example</strong>.  </blockquote>
<blockquote class="border-l-4 border-gray-300 pl-4 py-2 my-4 text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">For deeper exploration, click <strong class="font-semibold">â†’ Learn more</strong> to jump to Music Theory.</blockquote>

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2">A. Fundamentals</h2>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Scale Degree</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: <strong class="font-semibold">Numbers 1â€“7</strong> within a key. <strong class="font-semibold">1 = tonic</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: When the key changes, "1 (tonic)" moves (= movable do). Number relationships stay constant.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: In C major, 1â€“2â€“3 is <strong class="font-semibold">Câ€“Dâ€“E</strong>. In D major, it's <strong class="font-semibold">Dâ€“Eâ€“F#</strong>.  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">â†’ Learn more: <a href="/resources/music-theory#degrees" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">/resources/music-theory#degrees</a></p>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Interval</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Distance between two notes (perfect 5th, minor 3rd, etc.). Independent of key.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Use <strong class="font-semibold">degrees for progressions/melodies</strong>, <strong class="font-semibold">intervals for voicings</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Power chord = <strong class="font-semibold">1 (root) + 5th</strong>.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Key</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: The tonal center and pitch level of a piece.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: <strong class="font-semibold">Key selection</strong> determines 80% of singability. Capo comes after.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Chorus too high â†’ try half-step down (â€“1).  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">â†’ Learn more: <a href="/resources/music-theory#key-roman" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">/resources/music-theory#key-roman</a></p>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Diatonic</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: The "core members" of a key.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Build the skeleton with diatonic chords first to avoid confusion.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: D major diatonic chords: <strong class="font-semibold">D Em F#m G A Bm C#Â°</strong>.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Roman Numerals</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Chord notation based on scale degrees. <strong class="font-semibold">Uppercase = major / lowercase = minor / Â° = diminished</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Memorize progressions like <strong class="font-semibold">Iâ€“Vâ€“viâ€“IV</strong> for instant transposition.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Iâ€“Vâ€“viâ€“IV in C â†’ <strong class="font-semibold">Dâ€“Aâ€“Bmâ€“G</strong> in D.  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">â†’ Learn more: <a href="/resources/music-theory#roman" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">/resources/music-theory#roman</a></p>

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2">B. Chords and Symbols</h2>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Root</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: The starting point of a chord.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: When bass is present, <strong class="font-semibold">reduce root emphasis</strong> and prioritize 3rd/7th for clarity.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: In G7, let bass handle G, focus upper voices on <strong class="font-semibold">B (3rd) Â· F (7th)</strong>.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">3rd / 5th / 7th</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: 3rd = character, 5th = skeleton, 7th = directional arrow.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: The essential formula for accompaniment is <strong class="font-semibold">never skip 3rd/7th</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Voice lead <strong class="font-semibold">Bâ†’C</strong> (3rdâ†’root from G7â†’C) in the top voice.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Triad</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Three-note chord built on 1Â·3Â·5.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Moving just the <strong class="font-semibold">3rd</strong> changes the mood.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: C â†’ <strong class="font-semibold">Cm</strong> â†’ F (3rd moves Eâ†’Eâ™­).

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">7th Chord</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Triad + 7th.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: <strong class="font-semibold">V7 = strong resolution</strong>, <strong class="font-semibold">maj7 = dissolves</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: G â†’ <strong class="font-semibold">G7</strong> â†’ C / C â†’ <strong class="font-semibold">Cmaj7</strong> â†’ C.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">sus / add / slash</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: <strong class="font-semibold">sus</strong> suspends the 3rd, <strong class="font-semibold">add</strong> adds notes, <strong class="font-semibold">slash</strong> specifies bass note.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Sus creates "tension", slash enables <strong class="font-semibold">walking bass</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Dâ€“<strong class="font-semibold">Dsus4</strong>â€“D / Câ€“<strong class="font-semibold">C/E</strong>â€“F.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Inversion</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Rearranging which chord tone is in the bass (lowest note).  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Use <strong class="font-semibold">G/B, D/F#</strong> etc. for smooth bass lines.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Câ†’<strong class="font-semibold">G/B</strong>â†’Amâ†’<strong class="font-semibold">F/C</strong>.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Voicing</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Internal arrangement of chord tones.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Design the <strong class="font-semibold">top note</strong> to support the vocal melody.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Keep top notes <strong class="font-semibold">Eâ†’Eâ†’Fâ†’F</strong> through Câ†’Amâ†’Fâ†’G.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Form/Shape</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Fingering pattern (Open/Barre, etc.).  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Form â‰  voicing. <strong class="font-semibold">Same form with different arrangements</strong> changes the feel.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: C form with E on top vs. G on top sounds different.

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2">C. Progressions and Function</h2>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">T / S / D (Functional Harmony)</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: T = stable (I, vi), S = preparation (ii, IV), D = gravitational pull (V, viiÂ°).  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: <strong class="font-semibold">Tâ†’Sâ†’Dâ†’T</strong> framework reduces confusion.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Cï½œFï½œGï½œC.  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">â†’ Learn more: <a href="/resources/music-theory#tsd" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">/resources/music-theory#tsd</a></p>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Cadence</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Resolution patterns (Vâ†’I / IVâ†’I / Vâ†’vi / etc.).  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Use <strong class="font-semibold">Vâ†’I at chorus start</strong> as a clear flag.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: G7â†’C (authentic cadence).

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Secondary Dominant (V/â—‹â—‹)</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Temporarily treat the target chord as tonic and approach with its V7.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: <strong class="font-semibold">1â€“2 spot uses</strong> create maximum impact.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: In D, <strong class="font-semibold">E7â†’A</strong> (V/Vâ†’V).  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">â†’ Learn more: <a href="/resources/music-theory#secondary" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">/resources/music-theory#secondary</a></p>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Modal Interchange (Borrowed Chords)</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Borrowing bVII, bVI, iv etc. from the parallel minor.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Works great with open strings. Adds a <strong class="font-semibold">sunset color</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Dâ€“Câ€“G (Iâ€“bVIIâ€“IV).  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">â†’ Learn more: <a href="/resources/music-theory#modal-interchange" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">/resources/music-theory#modal-interchange</a></p>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Tritone Substitution / Backdoor</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: V7â‡„bII7, or bVII7â†’I.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Use sparingly for rich color.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: A7â†’D becomes <strong class="font-semibold">Eâ™­7â†’D</strong>.  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">â†’ Learn more: <a href="/resources/music-theory#tritone-backdoor" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">/resources/music-theory#tritone-backdoor</a></p>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Passing Diminished</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Insert a chromatic bridge for just one beat.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Use <strong class="font-semibold">#ivoÂ°7</strong> etc. for smooth transitions.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Dï½œ<strong class="font-semibold">G#Â°7</strong>ï½œAï½œD.  
<p class="mb-4 leading-relaxed">â†’ Learn more: <a href="/resources/music-theory#diminished" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">/resources/music-theory#diminished</a></p>

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2">D. Extensions and Alterations</h2>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">9/11/13 (Extensions)</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Color tones above the 7th.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Add <strong class="font-semibold">just 1â€“2 targeted notes</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Cmaj7(9), Am7(9,11).

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Alterations (â™­9 / â™¯9 / â™¯11 / â™­13)</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Spices that shape dominant direction.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Align with chord tones of the resolution target.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: G7(â™­9)â†’Cmaj7 / G7(â™¯11)â†’Cmaj7.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Avoid Note</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Notes that clash within a specific chord.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Watch for <strong class="font-semibold">11 over major</strong> (half-step clash with 3rd).  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: F (11) on Cmaj7 needs careful handling.

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

<h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4 border-b pb-2">E. Practical Tips</h2>

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Harmonic Rhythm</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Duration of chord changes.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Create <strong class="font-semibold">contrast</strong> between sections.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Verse = 1 bar, chorus = 2 beats.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Line ClichÃ©</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Chromatic inner voice movement.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Iâ€“Imaj7â€“I7â€“IV is simple and effective.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Câ€“Cmaj7â€“C7â€“F.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Pedal Point</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: Sustaining one note throughout changes.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: Open string pedals are a guitar superpower.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Keep high strings open while changing chords below.

<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Capo / Shaped / Sounding</h3>
<strong class="font-semibold">Definition</strong>: <strong class="font-semibold">Shaped = finger positions, Sounding = actual pitches</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Guitar Note</strong>: <strong class="font-semibold">Decide key first, capo second</strong>.  
<strong class="font-semibold">Example</strong>: Match vocal with â€“2, then add Capo 2 to use C shapes.

<hr class="my-8 border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-600" />

